AB  - This paper uses a unique data set of local governments' bond issuance, expenditure, and employment to study the impact that the monoline insurance industry's demise has on local governments' operations. To show causality, I use an instrumental variable approach that exploits persistent insurance relationships and the cross-sectional variation in insurers' exposure to high-quality residential mortgage-backed securities. Governments associated with ailing insurers issued less debt, cut expenditures, and hired fewer workers. These effects are concentrated among opaque governments and are persistent. Partial equilibrium calculations show that affected governments' aggregate expenditures and employment levels in 2017 would have been close to 10% higher if bond insurance had remained available.
